{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656577"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:15:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:15:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18749"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18749"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11481"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77326"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11481"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18749"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62833"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10474"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26575"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26581"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77326"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman is being examined for dizziness. The clinician asks her to focus on their nose while rotating her head from side to side.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the vestibulo-ocular reflex being tested?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Produces nystagmus to reset eye position","Stabilises head position relative to gravity","Generates eye movements in the same direction as head rotation","Triggers postural adjustments of neck muscles","Maintains gaze fixation through equal and opposite eye movements"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe vestibulo-ocular reflex \u003Cstrong\u003Emaintains gaze fixation through equal and opposite eye movements\u003C/strong\u003E when the head moves. When the head rotates in one direction, the eyes automatically move in the opposite direction by an equal amount, allowing stable vision during head movement.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerates eye movements in the same direction as head rotation\u003C/strong\u003E - This would worsen visual instability rather than compensate for head movement\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduces nystagmus to reset eye position\u003C/strong\u003E - Nystagmus is a pathological finding, not part of the normal reflex\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStabilises head position relative to gravity\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the vestibulocollic reflex, not the vestibulo-ocular reflex\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETriggers postural adjustments of neck muscles\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of the vestibulospinal reflex\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe reflex involves a three-neuron arc: primary vestibular afferents from the semicircular canals synapse in the vestibular nuclei, which project to motor nuclei controlling the extraocular muscles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The vestibulo-ocular reflex maintains visual fixation during head movement by producing compensatory eye movements in the opposite direction.","The vestibulo-ocular reflex involves a three-neuron arc from vestibular organs to extraocular muscles.","Head rotation activates semicircular canals which signal to vestibular nuclei and then to extraocular motor nuclei."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62833"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18749"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62833"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T16:12:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T16:13:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11481"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77326"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4942"},"attr